&gt; &gt;&gt;&gt;  Thanks to everyone who participated in Experiment 2.
&gt; &gt;&gt;&gt;
&gt; &gt;&gt;&gt; On Friday, 7/16/2010 I placed an object on top of my computer monitor,
&gt; &gt;&gt;&gt; right in front of me, and left it there until noon Denver time on Monday,
&gt; &gt;&gt;&gt; 7/19/2010. This experiment asked for participants to determine what that
&gt; &gt;&gt;&gt; object was. Vague or partial answers would not be counted (for example, just
&gt; &gt;&gt;&gt; giving a color, shape, size, what it&#39;s made of, etc): we&#39;re looking for what
&gt; &gt;&gt;&gt; it is. Answers anyone reveals after noon Denver time Monday won&#39;t count.
&gt; &gt;&gt;&gt; Participants can use their ghost boxes, EVP recorders, or any other means
&gt; &gt;&gt;&gt; they chose.
&gt; &gt;&gt;&gt;
&gt; &gt;&gt;&gt; In order to keep me honest, I took a picture of the object at the start
&gt; &gt;&gt;&gt; of the experiment and loaded it to the Files section (RJ folder) of this
&gt; &gt;&gt;&gt; group. The idea with this file is that you could download it at the
&gt; &gt;&gt;&gt; beginning of the experiment and &#39;keep it safe&#39; on your computer. Then at the
&gt; &gt;&gt;&gt; end of the experiment, I would post the password so you can reveal the
&gt; &gt;&gt;&gt; contents of the file. That way, you were in control of the original image
&gt; &gt;&gt;&gt; during the entire time, not me.
&gt; &gt;&gt;&gt;
&gt; &gt;&gt;&gt; Passworded pdf: http://tech. groups.yahoo. com/group/ EVP-ITC/files/
&gt; &gt;&gt;&gt; RJ/RJ20100716. pdf&lt;http://tech.groups.yahoo.com/group/EVP-ITC/files/RJ/RJ20100716.pdf&gt;
&gt; &gt;&gt;&gt;
&gt; &gt;&gt;&gt; The password for that file is: 2plus2isFour
&gt; &gt;&gt;&gt; Instructions, if you need them for the other files, are also in that RJ
&gt; &gt;&gt;&gt; folder.
&gt; &gt;&gt;&gt;
&gt; &gt;&gt;&gt; So to the results:
&gt; &gt;&gt;&gt;
&gt; &gt;&gt;&gt; Number of participants: 6
&gt; &gt;&gt;&gt; Total tries: 29
&gt; &gt;&gt;&gt; Ambiguous answers: 0
&gt; &gt;&gt;&gt; Correct answers: 0
&gt; &gt;&gt;&gt;
&gt; &gt;&gt;&gt; Object: Chair
&gt; &gt;&gt;&gt; Object picture: http://tech. groups.yahoo. com/group/ EVP-ITC/files/
&gt; &gt;&gt;&gt; RJ/RJ20100716. jpg&lt;http://tech.groups.yahoo.com/group/EVP-ITC/files/RJ/RJ20100716.jpg&gt;
&gt; &gt;&gt;&gt;
&gt; &gt;&gt;&gt; As a little side experiment, on Monday I also asked if anyone had gotten
&gt; &gt;&gt;&gt; any answers that might indicate an article of clothing (though I did not say
&gt; &gt;&gt;&gt; why I was asking). One theory is that the human operator can be influenced
&gt; &gt;&gt;&gt; by things they already know or suspect, and so interpret audio with their
&gt; &gt;&gt;&gt; own personal &#39;educated guesses&#39;, that would differ from what they would hear
&gt; &gt;&gt;&gt; had they not known those things. This side experiment did indicate some
&gt; &gt;&gt;&gt; support for that theory, since before I mentioned &#39;articles of clothing&#39;, no
&gt; &gt;&gt;&gt; one included an article of clothing in their results. But after I mentioned
&gt; &gt;&gt;&gt; it, several reports of clothing began to appear. I did not add these tries
&gt; &gt;&gt;&gt; to the results above.
&gt; &gt;&gt;&gt;
